### Explanation
The proof uses the fact that for any non-negative `t`, the absolute value of the integral of `g''` from `0` to `t` is bounded by the integral of the absolute value of `g''` from `0` to `t`. This is established by the lemma `abs_int_le_int_abs`. 

To compare the integrals over `[0, 1]`, we use the monotonicity of the integral. Specifically, if for every `t ∈ [0, 1]`, `|∫_{0}^{t} g'' s ds| ≤ ∫_{0}^{t} |g'' s| ds`, then integrating both sides over `[0, 1]` preserves the inequality. 

The continuity of the relevant functions ensures that the integrals are well-defined and that we can apply the monotonicity property. The final step is a straightforward calculation to confirm that the right-hand side matches the desired form. 

Note that this proof does not require any additional imports and only uses the given lemmas and basic properties of integrals. The rest of the proof context is not modified. 

